<Base title="Context Is Architecture — Augmented Engineering">
  <PatternPage number="3" title="Context Is Architecture" subtitle="Agents only see what's auto-loaded. Everything else is invisible. Design accordingly.">

    <p>Your agent isn't ignoring your docs because they're bad. It's ignoring them because they're <em>below the cliff</em>.</p>

    <p>AI agents don't browse. They load what's auto-loaded (CLAUDE.md, project instructions, memory files) and ignore everything else. A well-written runbook in <code>docs/RUNBOOK.md</code> has <em>zero impact</em> unless something triggers the agent to open it. This is the <strong>auto-loading cliff</strong>.</p>

    <div class="illustration-wrap">
      <IllustrationCliff />
    </div>

    <h2>What Crosses the Cliff</h2>

    <p>Descriptive labels don't cross it. Task-triggered pointers do.</p>

    <pre><code>Doesn't work:
| What              | Where              |
| API troubleshooting | docs/api-quirks.md |

Works:
| When              | Read               |
| API returns 422   | docs/api-quirks.md |</code></pre>

    <p>"API troubleshooting" is a category the agent has to decide is relevant. "API returns 422" is a situation the agent recognizes it's in. The first requires interpretation; the second is a match condition.</p>

    <div class="monday-box">
      <h3>Try This Monday</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Open your CLAUDE.md (or equivalent). Replace every descriptive "what" label with a task-triggered "when" condition.</li>
        <li>Identify your most important doc below the cliff. Add a task-triggered pointer from the auto-loaded file.</li>
        <li>Next time your agent ignores something obvious: was it below the cliff? If yes, the fix is a pointer, not better docs.</li>
        <li>Keep the auto-loaded file lean. Every line competes for attention. Demote anything that hasn't prevented a mistake recently.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Where This Comes From</h2>

    <div class="evidence-box">
      <p><strong>From agent-ready-projects:</strong> Discovered across 100+ agent sessions. Three independent agents audited three project types and converged on the same findings. The guide's own example was caught violating its own advice — using descriptive labels instead of task triggers.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Documentation quality for AI agents is measured by <strong>self-navigation, not accuracy.</strong> A perfectly accurate doc that no agent reads is worse than an approximate pointer that triggers the right lookup at the right time.</p>

    <div class="caveat-box">
      <h3>Honest Limitations</h3>
      <p>The auto-loading cliff is observed primarily with Claude Code. Other tools (Cursor, Copilot, Codex) have their own boundaries that may behave differently. The principle (agents don't browse) is likely general; the specific patterns are tested on one tool family by one researcher.</p>
    </div>

  </PatternPage>
</Base>
